The results of different scavengers on the photo-degradation of (Er3+/TiO2) NCs under visible light irradiation were examined to determine the reactive oxygen species that control the catalytic action (Fig. 13). The •OH was scavenged via using isopropanol (IPA) (10 mM), where h+ was scavenged with EDTA disodium (5 μM).To determine the effect of the absence of an electron scavenger on MB degradation operation, a single set was run without H2O2, as shown in Fig. 13. Following the addition of the above additives, the catalytic degradation efficiency of (Er3+/TiO2) NCs against MB was altered, denoting the sequence: EDTA disodium < IPA < without additives < H2O2. As a result, after removing H2O2, the degradation of MB using (Er3+/TiO2) NCs was significantly reduced (Fig. 13). This elucidates the role of electrons and oxygen peroxide radicals in the oxidation of MB underneath the visible-light illumination since the presence of electrons allowed the reduction of H2O2 to create •O2−, as shown below:Fig. 13
